#. REF: pts-vp-pli5.351, sc14
msgctxt "sn55.6:14.1"
msgid "“Tasmātiha, thapatayo, sambādho gharāvāso rajāpatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā. "
msgstr "“Well then, chamberlains, living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open. "

msgctxt "sn55.6:14.2"
msgid "Alañca pana vo, thapatayo, appamādāyā”ti. "
msgstr "Just this much is enough to be diligent.” "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn55.6:14.3"
msgid "“Atthi kho no, bhante, etamhā sambādhā añño sambādho sambādhataro ceva sambādhasaṅkhātataro cā”ti. "
msgstr "“Sir, for us there is something that’s even more cramped than that, and is considered as such.” "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn55.6:14.4"
msgid "“Katamo pana vo, thapatayo, etamhā sambādhā añño sambādho sambādhataro ceva sambādhasaṅkhātataro cā”ti? "
msgstr "“What is that?” "

# NOTE: Given the intimate contact emphasized in the following passages, i think the ablative here is in respect to each of the chamberlains; i.e. each one of them seats a wife in front of them and one behind.
#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc15
msgctxt "sn55.6:15.1"
msgid "“Idha mayaṃ, bhante, yadā rājā pasenadi kosalo uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyātukāmo hoti, ye te rañño pasenadissa kosalassa nāgā opavayhā te kappetvā, yā tā rañño pasenadissa kosalassa pajāpatiyo piyā manāpā tā ekaṃ purato ekaṃ pacchato nisīdāpema. "
msgstr "“Sir, it’s when King Pasenadi of Kosala wants to go and visit a park. We have to harness and prepare his royal elephants. Then we have to seat his dear and beloved wives on the elephants, one in front of us, and one behind. "

# NOTE: BB renders both bhagini and kañña as “lady”. I am not sure of the significance of bhagini here: does it mean they are actually sisters (as Maya and Majapajapati)? Or is is simply an honorific?
msgctxt "sn55.6:15.2"
msgid "Tāsaṃ kho pana, bhante, bhaginīnaṃ evarūpo gandho hoti, seyyathāpi nāma gandhakaraṇḍakassa tāvadeva vivariyamānassa, yathā taṃ rājakaññānaṃ gandhena vibhūsitānaṃ. "
msgstr "Those sisters smell like a freshly opened perfume box; that’s how the royal ladies smell with makeup on. "

# NOTE: The exact sense of sukhedhita is a little obscure. i think BB’s “delicately nurtured” is derived from MN 82/Pj1. However at Ja 547 we have “Yassā mudutalā hatthā, caraṇā ca sukhedhitā; … Yassā mudutalā pādā, caraṇā ca sukhedhitā;” and at Ja 543 “hatthapādā sukhedhitā”. In neither case does the concept of “nurtured” seem relevant; the point is simply that their feet and hands, or their life, is “delicate”.
msgctxt "sn55.6:15.3"
msgid "Tāsaṃ kho pana, bhante, bhaginīnaṃ evarūpo kāyasamphasso hoti, seyyathāpi nāma tūlapicuno vā kappāsapicuno vā, yathā taṃ rājakaññānaṃ sukhedhitānaṃ. "
msgstr "The touch of those sisters is like a tuft of cotton-wool or kapok; that’s how dainty the royal ladies are. "

msgctxt "sn55.6:15.4"
msgid "Tasmiṃ kho pana, bhante, samaye nāgopi rakkhitabbo hoti, tāpi bhaginiyo rakkhitabbā honti, attāpi rakkhitabbo hoti. "
msgstr "Now at that time we must look after the elephants, the sisters, and ourselves. "

msgctxt "sn55.6:15.5"
msgid "Na kho pana mayaṃ, bhante, abhijānāma tāsu bhaginīsu pāpakaṃ cittaṃ uppādetā. "
msgstr "But we don’t recall having a bad thought regarding those sisters. "

msgctxt "sn55.6:15.6"
msgid "Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, etamhā sambādhā añño sambādho sambādhataro ceva sambādhasaṅkhātataro cā”ti. "
msgstr "This is that thing that’s even more cramped than that, and is considered as such.” "

